TITLE: Large Items Discarded on Private Property
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
Subject: Property Code Violation Report – Abandoned Furniture and Building Debris
Date: November 16, 2025
To: Department of Neighborhood Services
City: Milwaukee, WI
Report:
This is a formal report regarding the property located at 2853 N 9th St, Milwaukee, WI, where the property owner has left large furniture items (white chest) and building debris (fallen siding) on the exterior lot. These items have been left uncollected for an extended period, creating obstacles, safety hazards, and potential rodent harborage.
Observed Violations:
Accumulation of junk/rubbish (Furniture and debris): In violation of Milwaukee Code Chapter 200 – Lot Maintenance Standards and Chapter 275?81 – Sanitary Conditions, which prohibit the accumulation of rubbish, waste, or other materials that create a health, safety, or fire hazard.
Rodent Harborage: The abandoned furniture and fallen siding provide shelter for rats and other pests, also violating Chapter 200 – Rodent Harborage Standards.
Neglect of Property Maintenance: Failure to remove fallen siding and maintain the exterior of the property constitutes a violation of the Vacant Building / Property Maintenance Ordinance, even if the property is not formally vacant.
Requested Action:
Please investigate this property for code violations and take appropriate enforcement action, including removal of abandoned furniture and building debris to mitigate risks to public health and neighborhood safety.
Reported by: Block 2800 N 9th St, Milwaukee, WI
Thank you for your prompt attention to this matter.

Affected Property: 2860 N 10th St #2858, Milwaukee, WI 53206
Report Date: November 16, 2025
Reported by: The 2800 Block of N 9th St, Milwaukee, WI 53206

1. Description of the Condition Observed
The city-owned vacant lot at 2860 N 10th St #2858,  has been observed to have:

Tall grass and overgrown shrubs along the meridian wall shared with the neighboring property.

Areas where wind has caused trash and debris to accumulate among the overgrown vegetation.

These conditions create public health and safety hazards, provide shelter for rodents and pests, and negatively impact the neighborhood’s appearance and safety.

2. Possible Municipal Code Violations

According to the Milwaukee Code of Ordinances, Chapter 275 – Building Maintenance Code, Sections 275-32 and 275-39:

Vacant lots must be maintained free from tall grass, weeds, brush, and debris.

Owners (or city custodians, for city-owned lots) must prevent conditions that attract rodents or create nuisances, including accumulation of trash due to wind in overgrown areas.

Overgrown vegetation along walls shared with neighboring properties can contribute to hazards or vermin problems, and thus constitutes a violation.

3. Associated Risks

Accumulation of windblown debris and litter.
Shelter and harborage for rodents and insects.
Fire hazard from dry tall grass and brush.

Negative impact on neighboring property and overall neighborhood appearance.

4. Recommendation

It is recommended that the Department of Neighborhood Services (DNS) or the city:

Inspect the vacant lot at 2858 N 10th St immediately.
Require that the lot be mowed and trimmed, including removal of overgrown shrubs along the shared meridian wall.

Remove accu

TITLE: Damaged City Tree
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION: Hi, this is a strange request, but we noticed some damage to one of our small terrace trees. We looked at our ring camera, and it appears that on 11/12 at around 2:45pm, an electric worker who had been working on the power lines at our intersection took a machete/large knife to our tree randomly??? For fun??? On the video, the other worker told him to stop. If possible, could someone come take a look at the tree and see if the bark needs any covering or something so the tree doesn't sustain permanent damage? He hacked into the trunk a fair amount (I've attached a screenshot of the incident). I also wanted to let you know in case this crew caused similar damage to other city trees...I'm happy to share our camera footage in case the city would like to pursue damages with We Energies. Thanks for all you do!

TITLE: Exterior of Building in Disrepair
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
BUILDING MAINTENANCE CODE VIOLATION REPORT
Affected Property: 2865 N 9th St, Milwaukee, WI 53206
Report Date: November 16, 2025
Reported by: The 2800 Block of N 9th St, Milwaukee, WI 53206

1. Description of the Condition Observed

At the property located at 2865 N 9th St, it was observed that the front upper area of the house is missing siding (exterior cladding). A significant section of the exterior wall is exposed.

The missing siding allows moisture to enter, contributes to structural deterioration, and indicates insufficient exterior maintenance.

2. Possible Municipal Code Violation

According to the Milwaukee Code of Ordinances, Chapter 275 – Building Maintenance Code, Section 275-32 (Exterior Structure):

All exterior surfaces must be free of holes, breaks, loose or rotted boards.

Exterior walls must not have conditions that allow the entry of rain or moisture.

All exterior surfaces must be maintained in good repair, including siding and protective coverings.

The missing siding at the upper front of the home constitutes a clear violation of the required exterior maintenance standards.

3. Associated Risks

Water infiltration into interior walls and structural components.

Potential mold growth and interior damage.
Progressive structural deterioration where the siding is missing.

Pest intrusion through exposed exterior areas.
Negative impact on the value and appearance of the property and neighborhood.

4. Recommendation

It is recommended that the property owner or responsible party:

Replace or install the missing siding on the upper front area of the home.

Ensure the exterior cladding is properly secured and sealed.
Conduct a full inspection of the rest of the exterior to ensure full compliance with code requiremen

BUILDING MAINTENANCE CODE VIOLATION REPORT

Affected Property: 2853 N 9th St, Milwaukee, WI 53206
Report Date: November 16, 2025
Reported by: The 2800 Block of N 9th St, Milwaukee, WI 53206

1. Description of the Condition Observed

At the property located at 2853 N 9th St, visible exterior deterioration was observed. The home shows missing or damaged siding on its exterior walls, exposing underlying surfaces to the weather.

This missing siding leaves the structure vulnerable to moisture penetration and indicates a lack of required exterior maintenance.

2. Possible Municipal Code Violation

According to the Milwaukee Code of Ordinances, Chapter 275 – Building Maintenance Code, Section 275-32 (Exterior Structure):

Exterior surfaces must be free of holes, breaks, loose or rotted boards.

Conditions that allow rain or moisture to enter must be prevented.
All exterior surfaces, including siding, must be maintained in good repair.

The absence or damage of siding constitutes a violation of the minimum exterior maintenance standards outlined by the city.

3. Associated Risks

Water infiltration into walls and interior floors.
Potential mold growth caused by moisture exposure.
Progressive structural deterioration of unprotected exterior surfaces.

Possible pest entry through exposed areas.
Negative impact on the appearance and value of the surrounding neighborhood.

4. Recommendation

It is recommended that the property owner or responsible party:

Replace or repair the missing or damaged siding immediately.

Ensure that all exterior cladding is properly secured, intact, and sealed.

Inspect the remainder of the exterior to ensure full compliance with code requirements.

TITLE: Mice/Roach Infestation
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
BUILDING MAINTENANCE CODE / VACANT PROPERTY VIOLATION REPORT

Affected Property: 2853 N 9th St, Milwaukee, WI 53206
Report Date: November 16, 2025
Reported by: The 2800 Block of N 9th St, Milwaukee, WI 53206

1. Description of the Condition Observed

The property at 2853 N 9th St is currently vacant and has been observed to be infested with rats. Multiple sightings have been reported of rodents leaving the building and crossing the alley, indicating an active infestation that poses health and safety risks to the neighborhood.

The building has not been properly maintained to prevent the presence or harborage of rodents, in violation of city codes for vacant properties.

2. Possible Municipal Code Violations

According to the Milwaukee Code of Ordinances, Chapter 275 – Building Maintenance Code, Section 275-32 (Exterior Structure and Maintenance) and related Vacant Building Registration (VBR) requirements:

Owners of vacant properties must maintain the premises free from rodents or vermin.

Foundations, basements, and all exterior areas must be protected against the entry of rodents or other animals.
Owners are responsible for extermination of insects, rodents, and other vermin in or about the premises.
Failure to address an active rodent infestation constitutes a violation of these maintenance requirements and poses a public health risk.

3. Associated Risks

Health hazards from rodent-borne diseases.
Potential structural damage from rodent activity.
Spread of rodents to adjacent properties and alleys.
Negative impact on the safety, sanitation, and value of the neighborhood.

TITLE: Traffic Signals
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION: I hope this finds you well. A few times now, I have noticed this residential intersection near MacDowell Montessori School and off of Juneau Playfield can have spots of heavy pedestrian traffic including buses, garbage trucks, cars, students & parents, and other local residents passing through. This intersection currently only has a Two-Way Stop sign (not a traffic light), and may be better served as a Four-Way Stop, at least at certain times of the day, as cars on 66th Street do not stop and some are so accustomed to this route that they do not even slow down. Thank you for your assistance in making wise considerations for action to maintain a safe neighborhood, and have a nice day!

Traffic Signals
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
I was driving from the North, Southbound on Milwaukee Street at approximately 9am on a Wednesday.  I got stopped at a red light (which is normal), and then proceeded to sit at the intersection of Milwaukee St and Kilbourne Ave for 5 minutes (the entire duration of the Bee Gees song Staying Alive until the light turned Green.

It turns out that the MKE Hop gets traffic light precedence throughout it's route.... this is ridiculous.  First, you hardly see anyone use the MKE HOP, second, the ability for vehicles to flow through traffic is greatly impeded, causing more delays and congestion on the city streets.

I'd imagine that the entire MKE Hop route is number 1 priority when it comes to traffic moving through the streets, which is absurd and the entire system needs to be changed.  Who thought of this when determining plans and route?

Please fix the traffic lights to allow the MKE Hop to flow with the general traffic of normal vehicles, and not the Hop dictating traffic signals.

TITLE: Traffic Signals
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
The Cherry Street Bridge over the Milwaukee River has been out for the majority of 2025.  The traffic signal at the intersection of Water St and Cherry St still believes or understands that the bridge is still in working order.

Unfortunately, this forces vehicles to stop at a red light when there is no cross traffic, causing significant congestion and delays that back up Water St and Knapp St.  Who determines the traffic signal precedence at this location?  And how are traffic lights determined in the city? (sensor, timer, etc).

This needs to be fixed.  There also needs to better forethought regarding the flow, planning, and execution, and the impact it has on the general public.

TITLE: Defective Wiring, Outlets or Fixtures
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION: I moved into my apartment on 9/5. On this day, 4 outlets did not work (two in bedroom, two in living room). I put in a maintenance request and they have not been fixed. This includes electricity to the refrigerator and freezer - I have not been able to store my food in the apartment since. I submitted another maintenance request immediately when this issue occurred, and the issue still has not been solved. I have contacted my landlord/maintenance multiple times, and they will not give me any information about when they will fix the issue or send someone in to fix it. At the moment, I only have 3 working outlets. Without working outlets and refrigerator, the apartment is unlivable, and I am also concerned about a fire starting due to the faulty electricity.

Thank you so much! 
Grace

TITLE: Interior of Building in Disrepair
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
A severe sewage backup occurred in the basement. The sump pumps failed to handle the volume of water, causing sewage to flood the entire basement area, including the staircase. The water remained for approximately three days before the exterior floodwaters receded enough to allow access for pumping.

Due to the prolonged exposure to sewage:

Drywall had to be removed.

Furance: Stopped working circut board need to be replaced.

Water Heater: stopped working will need to be replaced. 

The entire basement floor and base areas required repeated treatment with bleach and bacterial enzyme to sanitize the space.

Dehumidifiers were purchased and used extensively to remove moisture.

The incident caused significant damage, resulting in cracked interior walls that suggest potential foundation damage.

TITLE: Miscellaneous Street Maintenance Request
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION: I live at 528 E Holt Ave, There is a public sidewalk and walkway tunnel that goes under the railroad tracks right next to the property, Last year a water main broke and flooded the tunnel. The mud and debris was never cleaned up  by the city and the tunnel is not accessible as people would have to walk through the thick layer of mud. Not having access to the tunnel has created s public safety concern as people are now climbing up the steep hill and crossing over the railroad tracks. Many people and children rely on the walkway and I am concerned that someone will be hit by a train or fall down the steep hill if the tunnel is not cleaned up or cleared out. Myself and the rest of my neighborhood would appreciate the tunnel being cleared and accessible again.

Subject: Urgent Safety Concern – Hazardous Pothole on Grant Blvd and Meinecke St.

Dear Department of Public Works,

I am writing to urgently report a very large and hazardous pothole located on Grant Blvd. at the intersection with Meinecke St. The pothole spans more than half of the street, and debris is dislodged whenever vehicles drive over it. This poses a serious danger to children who play nearby, pedestrians, and parked vehicles.

The condition is deteriorating rapidly, and I am deeply concerned about the risk of accidents or injuries if it is not addressed promptly. I respectfully request immediate attention and repair of this matter before it worsens further.

Thank you for your prompt response and commitment to community safety.

Respectfully,
Mrs. Jefferson 
Homeowner

OBJECTDESC: 1135 S CESAR E CHAVEZ DR, MILWAUKEE, WI, 53204-2266
TITLE: Exterior of Building in Disrepair
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
Once a neighborhood dental clinic, this property has been closed for several years and now sits vacant and neglected. The exterior is covered in large graffiti murals and tags, giving it an urban, distressed appearance. Windows are broken or boarded up, and the surrounding grounds show signs of long-term disuse.

Inside, the building is in deteriorated condition, with signs of unauthorized entry and evidence that homeless individuals frequently seek shelter there. Squatters have occupied parts of the property, contributing to further wear and safety concerns.

Overall, the site reflects years of abandonment, presenting both challenges and potential for redevelopment with proper restoration and security measures.

TITLE: Other Animal Problem
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION: On a daily basis the property at 7908 W Herbert has a dog in the backyard constantly barking all day & into the night. Barking with whining as if he isn’t being taken care of.  This same resident had complaints against them for beating their previous dog and the police showed up for it. I witnessed it through my fence. Now they have this other dog that sounds much bigger and is always outside barking & whining. 7908 W Herbert Ave is the address where this is taking place. The yard has a massive trampoline & a good size pool for the kids. But NO attention or care  is being given to this dog. It’s being neglected & most likely mentally & physically abused .  I have 4 dogs of my own and this treatment of this poor dog is unacceptable. Being an army vet, prior law enforcement this is very disturbing to me. If someone can’t take care of or treat a pet as part of a family then there is no need to have a pet in the first place. Before this dog suffers anymore abuse PLEASE HAVE someone investigate this problem and get this dog to a family that cares. The current owners obviously don’t care. They physical abused their first dog (I witnessed that) & now the same treatment to the current dog. PLEASE HELP ASAP!!!!!!!!!

TITLE: Contractor Complaint
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
City of Milwaukee 
Subject: Formal Complaint Regarding Lead Lateral Replacement Work and Property Damage

I am submitting this letter as a formal complaint regarding the service I received last November at 220 E. Clarke St. when the lead lateral was replaced from the street to my basement. Unfortunately, the work performed has left my property in an unacceptable and unsafe condition, and despite my attempts to resolve this matter with the contractor, it remains unresolved.

Unfinished Yard and Safety Hazards
* My yard is still torn up from the excavation, which makes it difficult to mow and maintain.
* Concrete forms from sidewalk pour remain in place with iron spikes protruding from the ground, posing a clear safety hazard.
* It appears that no one intends to return and properly restore the property.

Damage to Electrical Service 
During the excavation, the contractor struck the electrical service drop with their excavator, knocking it completely off the house. These wires supply power from the utility pole to my property. I was never contacted about this incident. Instead, my tenants were told that power would be restored around noon that day as this happened in the morning. I did not become aware of the outage until 11:00 p.m., when my tenants called upset to report that the house was really cold and still without power.
The electrical service was reattached in a questionable manner:
* The ceramic-headed screw-in bolt that secures the service wires to the house was damaged and now sits crooked in my opinion.
* The metal mast mounted to the side of my property is missing its protective cap. This mast houses the electrical wires running from the exterior of my home to the interior basement panel, and without the cap, the connection is potentially exposed.
* A piece of

TITLE: Potholes
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
I have lived in the Washington Heights area on and off since 1992 owning a home on 60th street for 14 years. For past 8 years since coming back to Milwaukee and neighbor hood I have resided on the corner of 58th and Vliet in a 4 family rental unit. . 58th street along with both 57th street, and 59th street are  and have been in deplorable condition. Several times i have contacted alderman Murphy before his retirement to report some huge pot holes and generally hazardous conditions of the streets, in particular 58th street from Vliet street south to the entrance to Hawthorne Glen park. Alderman Murphy always responded by sending out a DPW crew to patch up the worst of the pot holes and terrible condition of 58th street only to have the patches quickly disappear or just placing a band aide on a much more severe general street condition. There is no way to drive down 58th south from Vliet street avoiding multiple pot holes and generally terrible road surface. Are there any plans to at least consider the less costly resurfacing process that the city has employed on certain streets in the city to apply a smoother and sager driving service without complete street, curb, sidewalk replacement. Its truly a situation that has gone on far too long and I will begin to gather signatures or testimonies from my neighbors to validate my concerns. Would be grateful for any response from Alderman or the DPW division responsible for such matters. Thank You. Steve Hooser 1391 n. 58th St. #1 414-975-4564 email, stephenhooser53@gmail.com 
the actual streets are 57, 58th, and 59th streets from vliet south to Mckinley.

TITLE: Exterior of Building in Disrepair
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
I moved 1531 s 23rd st Milwaukee Wisconsin 53204 Single house Front Door with 3 bedrooms into this house only one month ago with my mother and siblings. We have a signed lease until May 12, 2026, but the landlord and his wife are already trying to push us out. He said he doesn’t want to evict us, but wants us to move to another house not in the agreement.



My mother is a single mom. I am the only one working full-time, paying rent, and taking responsibility. Since we moved in, the landlord has refused to fix anything. When we ask for basic repairs, he blames me and avoids doing what a landlord is supposed to do.

His wife insulted my mother, and his wife spoke to her in an aggressive and disrespectful way including him the homeowner . I feel this is harassment. We don’t feel safe. We are still paying rent every month and just want to live here peacefully until our lease ends.

I want to speak with someone to investigate this and talk to the landlord. He should follow the lease and take care of his responsibilities as a property owner.

TITLE: Garage in Disrepair
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION: This building is disturbingly not secure. Last week a person was shot inside the building during an Attempted robbery because people who don’t live here were able to get inside the garage. Once someone gets in the garage, which isn’t hard, they can go anywhere in the building. The doors to the stairs or the elevator do not lock. Some homeless man was just sleeping in his own throw up where the mailboxes were as I was taking my daughters to the dentist on Monday. Homeless people come in this building where tenants pay rent and sleep by the mailboxes or in the stairwell for free everyday. The property manager has yet to have people come fix or even look at the garage and doors that don’t lock since the shooting.

TITLE: Other Animal Problem
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION: My tenant Julio Ibarra has a dog onsite in the 2nd for apt. When I was there to collect rent, the dog lunged to attack me and my 9 yr old son. The dog was on leash but not under control by Julios 14 yr old son. The dog is vicious and needs to be reported as potentially dangerous. It's ok to have a dog that's protective but if you can't control it that's a public nuisance. I asked for the pets registration and pet liability insurance from the tenant. I haven't received it yet. When I asked the tenant on the 1St floor if she's had similar experiences with the dog, she said it went after her twins one day and she has to be careful when she leaves her apt with the children. A dog like this shouldn't be around children. If this happens again I want the dog off my property or removed by the proper authorities.

TITLE: Light Nuisance
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
I am writing to file a light nuisance complaint concerning the flashing camera cart with a police-style light located in the parking lot of McDonald’s at 2520 W National Ave, Milwaukee, WI.

The flashing blue light from this camera cart shines directly past my closed blinds and into my apartment at night, located further down the road at 902 S 25th St. This constant and disruptive light has made it difficult to sleep and has become a significant nuisance.

I attempted to contact McDonald's directly to address the issue, but unfortunately, I did not receive any response. I also called their corporate toll-free number, but no one answered that call either. I am not sure whether McDonald's will take action on their own, so I am reaching out to your department in hopes that you can help resolve this situation.

I would like to request that the flashing blue light be turned off during the night or that the camera cart be moved to another part of the parking lot where the light does not affect nearby residents. This issue is causing unnecessary disturbance and discomfort, and I would appreciate any assistance you can provide in addressing it.

Thank you for your attention to this matter. I look forward to your response and any steps you may take to resolve this nuisance.

TITLE: Mice/Roach Infestation
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
I am writing to formally file a complaint regarding a recurring mice infestation in my rental unit at **902 S. 25th St., Unit #5**, Milwaukee, WI 53204. Over the past several weeks, I have noticed the presence of one or two mice on and off within the apartment, and despite my repeated concerns to my landlord, **Devoe Rentals LLC**, the issue has not been adequately addressed.

I have informed the landlord on several occasions about the mice problem, but their response has been dismissive and lacking in action. They have offered excuses and have not taken any concrete steps to resolve the issue. As a tenant, I am paying **$450 per month** for this rental, and I believe it is unacceptable for the landlord to ignore this serious health and safety concern.

I understand that **Devoe Rentals LLC** has a history of similar complaints with your department, and I am requesting that appropriate action be taken against this landlord for their failure to maintain the property in a habitable condition. The continued presence of pests in my apartment makes it difficult for me to live in the space comfortably, and I should not have to endure this while paying rent.

I am asking that you investigate this matter further and hold the landlord accountable for not addressing the issue. It is not fair to continue to pay rent in these conditions when they have not taken the necessary steps to address the problem.

Thank you for your attention to this matter. I look forward to hearing from you soon.

TITLE: Plumbing Problem
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
I am submitting a formal complaint regarding a persistent plumbing issue at **902 S 25th St, Milwaukee, WI 53204**, specifically with the second-floor bathroom tub.

The issue is that the bathtub in this bathroom fills with water whenever the shower head is in use, for no apparent reason. I am unsure whether this is an ongoing issue that has not been reported previously, or if it is a new problem that has gone unnoticed. Regardless, it is causing inconvenience and concerns regarding potential water damage or further plumbing complications.

I have informed my landlord, **Devoe Rentals LLC**, about this problem on several occasions, but they have refused to take any action or address the issue in any way. This lack of response has prompted me to reach out to your department for assistance.

Additionally, I have come to learn that Devoe Rentals LLC has a **history of complaints with the Milwaukee Department of Neighborhood Services**. It appears that they have a pattern of neglecting tenant concerns and providing substandard living conditions while continuing to collect rent payments from hard-working Milwaukee residents. It is disheartening to see that these landlords appear to operate without regard for the well-being or safety of their tenants.

Given the serious nature of the plumbing issue, the landlord’s failure to address it, and their history of neglect, I am requesting that the **Milwaukee Department of Neighborhood Services investigate this matter** as soon as possible. I would appreciate any assistance you can provide in ensuring that this issue is resolved in a timely and professional manner.

Thank you for your attention to this complaint. I look forward to your prompt response and resolution of this matter.

They also have overgrowth of weeds and vines that climbs our fence every summer, strangling our plants in our yard and causing our fence (3023) to lean. We sprayed our side with weed killer and now the debris is just laying dead in their driveway since last summer. I would assume that’s a fire hazard during burn advisories because it is dry, dead weeds. They also have jam packed gutters that cause water leakage into our basement and drown summer tomato plants in our gangways.

Talking to the owner doesn’t do anything. It actually makes things worse. The owner has previously threatening to burn down my house and rape me. So many calls have been placed about the child abuse, drunk driving, and screaming verbal altercations. SWAT has even been to the house. Each time the Police tell me to document any and every instance so that’s what I’m doing with this report. Thank you for your time.

TITLE: Scattered Litter and Debris on Private Property
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION:
A man in the neighborhood, Kevin Tietz, residing at 4835 N 63rd St, Milwaukee, WI 53218, is a public health hazard. Not only is he a hoarder within the home and in his car, which has caused a plethora of insects and vermin to encroach within his property, but his mental illness has progressed, which is decreasing our property values. Kevin throws food on the side walk and within his front yard including: pork knuckle bones, ribs, turkey carcasses, rice, corn flakes, various fruits and vegetables, eggs, marshmellos, hot dog buns, bagles, and other products to name a few which are left overs he receives from the food pantry. This leftover waste ends up in my front and back yard or under my car, including the bones and scraps. This has also attracted unwanted rodents and other vermin to the area, including excess squirrels, raccoons, crows, mice, and furthermore attracted the stray cat population. The cats now take harbor under my deck and urinate consistently, ruining my yard. The problem is that much of the food which is laid out goes uneaten as these animals are not adapted to eat items, such as marshmallows and corn flakes. Several neighbors, including Edward Steward, residing at 6221 N 63rd St, Milwaukee, WI 53218, also have expressed to me that this debris has become a problem within his yard. We have expressed our dissatisfaction with the problem to Kevin in a pleasant manner, but he does not take our complaints seriously and continues the pattern. This has occurred for over 2 years and has only increased in the past few months. I am seeking help to stop this. I am concerned for my health as I recently found a rodent within my garage, which I know is attributable to this increase in left out waste. 
I was only able to attach one photo, but I have plenty more to shar

TITLE: Other Miscellaneous Forestry Request
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION: The school does not pick up their leaves along the south and west sides of the property. I have lived down the road in this neighborhood for four years and every year the leaves pile-up along the sidewalk and alley. It is a nuisance for many reasons including that it makes the area look messy, it attracts garbage, people let their dogs poop all over it. I’ve also seen dead rodents buried in the leaves. I’d like my children to be able to play in the vicinity without being concerned about it. Also, In the winter, this area becomes a muddy mess and it’s so unnecessary if the school would just pick up these leaves year-round. I’ve attempted to contact the school directly but they do not have a public email that I could find.

TITLE: Interior of Building in Disrepair
CASECLOSUREREASONDESCRIPTION: I have been experiencing health issues since moving into this house in October. There is a storage room in the basement that has a very musty and mildew-like odor. You can’t see the source of the moisture, but you can smell it. In mid-December I first reported it to him. At first my landlord was very responsive and seemed to care. The first mold specialist that he sent looked at the room and said “oh, it’s a safe mold, if there is any mold” and did no testing whatsoever. Weeks later, I do my own mold testing and pay for it out of my own pocket. I followed the instructions exactly and tested in various areas in the room. Including by the pipe, by the walls (where the first mold specialist assumed there could be mold.) My testing showed Aspergillus, Penicillium, and Cladosporium was found. One of the samples I did right by the pipe and wall, and that was the most severe. I go to my landlord with all this information and share the reports and he sends a second mold specialist out to do his own testing. That was almost 3 weeks ago on January 13th and I haven’t heard one thing in response from my landlord about the results or any remediation plans. I think this is an uninhabitable condition for ME and MY family. I must be particularly sensitive to molds. A lot of people are so I’m not sure why everyone is downplaying this and not doing any further investigation. My dog is constantly itchy and can’t even stay at the house anymore. I am done being ignored by my landlord and I’m ready to figure out a solution or get me out of this house.

It's a great PR gesture for the city.   Urban planning journals talk about that strategy to mitigate urban CO2 generation.  Want Pictures?  Please forward to  Commissioner Kruschke.
